ages/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://www.cafenet.plus.com/The_Magicians_Tower/Images/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kuinrin>Kuinrin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#333333>(11/27/02 7:19:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7989.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Off topic technical questions (concerning routers)</span><hr size=1> Recently I hooked up a router in the house between my two computers.  Its a Linksys (wireless), and so far Ive had nothing but problems playing EQ.   I go linkdead after 10-15 minutes consistently.   I do some searching and see other have had simliar problems with Linksys routers.    My question is, have any of you experienced this same problem?   Would getting another brand of router fix this problem?   If so what would you recommend?    Now anytime I want to play I have to unplug the router and directly connect my Cable Modem.<br>
<br>
Thanks for any help<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kuinrin>Kuinrin</A> at: 11/27/02 7:23:03 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tenesu>Tenesu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#333333>(11/27/02 7:44:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7989.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  I've never had a problem</span><hr size=1> Wieh my netgear router.  However it is not a wireless router.  My guess is that you're getting interference from somewhere.  Is your computer close to the router or far away?  The strength of the signal deteriorates greately the farther you are away.  My advice, although this is a hassle, is to move your computer around and see you can get better reception in a different location.  If you do then you can probably move your router to another location in the house.  If you have a laptop this is much easier obviously.   Try to keep your computer/router away from heavy noise generators like tv's, microwaves, and most electric motors also. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cubicool>Cubicool</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#333333>(11/27/02 8:18:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7989.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I've never had a problem</span><hr size=1> Linksys &quot;routers&quot; *shudders* have a &quot;Keep Alive&quot; option that might be booting you. Try this. It may/maynot be able to detect your EQ activity. Play around with it.<br>
<br>
If the problem is reproducable, every 15 or so, it's not &quot;interference&quot;, otherwise you'd notice the behavior in everthing internet related - unless, of course, you already do. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drewcilla@themagicianstower>Drewcilla</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#333333>(11/27/02 8:18:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7989.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  linksys</span><hr size=1> this is a known problem with linksys routers with the flash bios over 1.40x.  and all the wireless ones have higher.  if you go to the forums at www.everquest.com they have some fix's for this.  Just search for linksys and you will get about 50 threads about this.<br>
<br>
i have not upgraded my flash bios just because of this.  i actually downgraded mine to 1.38 (not a wireless router) just so this would not happen.  <br>
<br>
Drewcilla<br>
